_CONTENT|
 #TopHead    QTML
 #SubHeader1 Readable
 #SubHeader2 Functional
 #SubHeader3 Versatile
 #Bulk1      QTML is a Markup/Markdown syntax and parser. The purpose of this
             is to have the functionality of html and css while still coming
             close to the quickness of writing basic markdown. Currently,
             the PDF exporting is done with PDFKit and WKHtmlToPdf.--
             --
             QTML looks for 3 different _blocks_. These are the *LAYOUT*,
             *CONTENT*, and *STYLE* blocks.--
             --
 #SH1        *LAYOUT* Block
 #D1         The layout block reads out very similar to html. Only with subtle
             differences focused on typing speed.
 #C1         \_div#Container.example|--
             &#9;\_p#ExampleId.example||\_ --
             |div\_
|CONTENT_

_STYLE|
body{
    font-family:arial;
    width:100%;
}
h1{
    font-size:26px;
}
p,
span{
    font-size:12px;
}
hr{
    margin-left:0px;
    margin-right:0px;
    padding-left:0px;
    padding-right:0px;
    width:100%;
}
#RuleBumpDown{
    margin-top:50px;
}
.header,
.subheader{
    color:grey;
    text-align:center;
}
.lcr-container{
    position:relative;
}
.left{
    position:absolute;
    left:0;
}
.left>p{
    text-align:left;
}
.center{
    position:absolute;
    display:block;
    width:100%;
}
.inner-center{
    display:block;
    width:auto;
    margin:0px auto;
}
.inner-center>p{
    text-align:center;
}
.right{
    position:absolute;
    right:0;
}
.right>p{
    text-align:right;
}
.sectionheader{
    font-size:18px;
    color:grey;
}
|STYLE_
